Article
Comparative characterization of human accelerated regions in neurons
Xiekui Cui1,12, Han Yang1,12, Charles Cai1, Cooper Beaman1, Xiaoyu Yang1, Hongjiang Liu1, Xingjie Ren1, Zachary Amador1, Ian R. Jones1,2, Kathleen C. Keough2,3, Meng Zhang4,5, Tyler Fair6,7, Armen Abnousi8, Shreya Mishra8, Zhen Ye1, Ming Hu8, Alex A. Pollen6,7, Katherine S. Pollard1,3,9,10 & Yin Shen1,7,11 ✉
Human accelerated regions (HARs) are conserved genomic loci that have experienced rapid nucleotide substitutions following the divergence from chimpanzees1,2. HARs are enrichedincandidateregulatoryregionsnearneurodevelopmentalgenes,suggesting their roles in gene regulation3. However, their target genes and functional contributions to human brain development remain largely uncharacterized. Here we elucidate the cis-regulatory functions of HARs in human and chimpanzee induced pluripotent stem (iPS) cell-induced excitatory neurons. Using genomic4 and chromatin looping information, we prioritized 20 HARs and their chimpanzee orthologues for functional characterization via single-cell CRISPR interference, and demonstrated their speciesspecific gene regulatory functions. Our findings reveal diverse functional outcomes of HAR-mediated cis-regulation in human neurons, including attenuated NPAS3 expression by altering the binding affinities of multiple transcription factors in HAR202 and maintaining iPS cell pluripotency and neuronal differentiation capacities through the upregulation of PUM2 by 2xHAR.319. Finally, we used prime editing to demonstrate differential enhancer activity caused by several HAR26;2xHAR.178 variants. In particular, we link one variant in HAR26;2xHAR.178 to elevated SOCS2 expression and increased neurite outgrowth in human neurons. Thus, our study sheds new light on the endogenous gene regulatory functions of HARs and their potential contribution to human brain evolution.
Humans (Homo sapiens) possess many distinct characteristics compared with our closest extant relative, the chimpanzee (Pan troglodytes). However, despite striking phenotypic differences, the genomes of humans and chimpanzees are remarkably similar, sharing approximately 99% sequence identity in consensus sequences5. Early comparative analyses have revealed that differences in protein-coding sequences do not fully explain observed differences between the two species6, suggesting that these characteristics may result from differences in non-coding regions. HARs, primarily located in the non-coding genome, are genomic loci that are evolutionarily conserved across mammals; however, in humans, HARs exhibit a statistically significant excess of nucleotide substitutions, suggesting accelerated evolution1,2,7. HARs are thought to function as developmental enhancers because they are enriched at loci associated with brain development and neurodevelopmental disorders such as autism spectrum disorder and schizophrenia8,9. Therefore, elucidating the regulatory functions of HARs could reveal insights into human brain evolution, development and function.
Recent studies using massively parallel reporter assays (MPRAs) have demonstrated that HARs and their chimpanzee orthologues exhibit species-specific enhancer activities4,10–12. For example, 293 of the 714 HARs and their chimpanzee orthologues exhibited significant enhancer activity in neural progenitor cells4. Although these studies provide much-needed functional annotation for HARs, considerable gaps remain in characterizing HARs within their native chromatin context and identifying their cognate target genes. HARs mainly scatter in poorly annotated intronic (36%) or intergenic (59%) regions3, with only eight experimentally characterized in their native chromatin context with target genes linked to distinctive human features8,10,13–18, motivating us to further characterize HARs and their target genes. We conducted comparative genomic analyses of the transcriptome, epigenome and chromatin interaction in human and chimpanzee iPS cell-induced excitatory neurons to elucidate the roles of HARs in transcriptional regulation. Furthermore, we prioritized and characterized 20 HARs and their chimpanzee orthologues via single-cell CRISPR
