interference (CRISPRi). Finally, we demonstrated the regulation of SOCS2 and its effects on neuritogenesis by HAR26;2xHAR.178 at base-pair resolution.
HARs exhibit enhancer functions in excitatory neurons To establish cellular models for comparative analysis of HARs and their chimpanzee orthologues, we introduced doxycycline-inducible Ngn2 at the AAVS1 locus in two chimpanzee iPS cell lines, creating isogenic, inducible i3N chimpanzee lines for generating excitatory neurons using the i3N human iPS cell differentiation protocol19 (Fig. 1a). Excitatory neurons induced from both human (WTC11 (ref. 19) and F12468 (ref. 20)) and chimpanzee (C3649 (ref. 21) and C3624 (ref. 22)) i3N iPS cell lines expressed the cortical neuron marker CUX1, the glutamatergic neuron marker VGLUT1 and the synaptic genes SYN1, SYP, SV2A and
GRIA1 (Extended Data Fig. 1a–c). Single-cell transcriptome analysis revealed that neurons from both species were homogeneous, expressing excitatory neuron markers (Extended Data Fig. 1d), and closely resembled developing human brain neurons23 (Fig. 1b). Differential gene expression analysis of bulk RNA sequencing (RNA-seq) datasets (Extended Data Fig.2a,b) identified 659 human-upregulated and 1,221 chimpanzee-upregulated genes (Fig. 1c). Human-upregulated genes are involved in axon development, synaptic signalling and function, whereas chimpanzee-upregulated genes are linked to organelle fission and nuclear division (Extended Data Fig. 2c and Supplementary Table 1). Next, we generated anti-H3K4me3 proximity ligation-assisted chromatin immunoprecipitation sequencing (PLAC-seq) and assay for transposase-accessible chromatin with high-throughput sequencing (ATAC-seq) datasets to characterize the epigenetic features of
