Fig. 1 | HARs exhibit enhancer function in excitatory neurons. a, iPS cell lines with knock-in of doxycycline-inducible Ngn2 in human and chimpanzee iPS cells and their induced excitatory neurons. Scale bars, 100 μM. b, Comparing transcriptomes of iPS cell-induced neurons with cells of the developing human cortex23. UMAP, uniform manifold approximation and projection. c, Differentially expressed genes in neurons based on human or chimpanzee assembly. NS, not significant. d, Number of HARs and their orthologues in groups I, II and III based on chromatin accessibility and gene interactions. e, Expression analysis of genes in groups I, II and III. Group I includes 374 and 377 genes interacting with accessible HARs or HAR orthologues, group II includes 346 and 274 genes interacting with non-accessible HARs or HAR orthologues, and group III includes 999 and 974 genes close to HARs or HAR orthologues but without interaction in neurons, respectively. For all genes, group I contains 9,972 and 9,071 genes interacting with accessible distal regions, group II includes 325 and
303 genes interacting with distal regions not overlapping ATAC-seq peaks, and group III includes 1,460 and 1,615 genes neighbouring but not interacting with distal regions, respectively. P values were calculated based on the two-sided Student’s t-test. The boxplot shows the median, interquartile range and whiskers extending up to 1.5 times the interquartile range, with outliers as dots. TPM, transcripts per million. f, Forest plot illustrates the odds ratio of the relationship between human-upregulated (n = 659) or chimpanzee-upregulated (n = 1,221) genes and HAR-related (n = 720) or HAR orthologue-related (n = 651) genes within the total 17,319 analysed genes. P values were calculated using the two-sided Fisher’s exact test. Error bars indicate 95% confidence intervals. g, Enrichment of transcription factor (TF) motifs in HARs and their orthologues in groups I and II. P values were calculated using the cumulative binomial distribution in HOMER with no multiple comparison adjustments.


Nature | www.nature.com | 3
3,257 previously nominated HARs10,11 and their chimpanzee orthologues (Supplementary Table 2) in neurons. We detected 222,554 and 207,087 significant H3K4me3-associated chromatin interactions at 5-kb resolution, averaging 22.2 and 17.3 interactions per promoter in human and chimpanzee neurons, respectively (Extended Data Fig. 3a and Supplementary Table 2). The median interaction distance was approximately 250 kb (Extended Data Fig. 3b), with approximately 82% interactions between promoters and other distal regions in both species (Extended Data Fig. 3c). Human (70.0%) and chimpanzee (67.9%) interactions were shared, a significantly higher overlap than expected by random chance, suggesting high conservation of active promoter-anchored chromatin loops (P < 0.001; Extended Data Fig. 3d,e). A significant number of open chromatin regions (approximately 54,000) were shared between species (P < 0.001; Extended Data Fig.3f,g). Finally, we observed an enrichment of overlapping accessible peaks (n = 32,000) in H3K4me3-associated chromatin-interacting regions between human (n = 49,793) and chimpanzee (n = 44,600) neurons (P < 0.001; Extended Data Fig.3h,i). Together, NGN2-induced excitatory neurons from both species are molecularly similar, enabling appropriate comparative analysis between HARs and their chimpanzee orthologues. In human neurons, 3,567 chromatin interactions overlapped with 830 HARs (Extended Data Fig. 3j), involving 1,333 HAR-interacting genes. These HAR-related chromatin interactions account for 63.5% (374 of 589) and 41.4% (521 of 1,257) of those identified by using excitatory neurons isolated from developmental and adult cortical tissues24,25, respectively, suggesting that iPS cell-induced neurons more closely resemble HAR-related chromatin interactions in primary neurons from the developing cortex (Extended Data Fig. 3k). Next, we categorized the genes into three distinct groups: group I consists of genes interacting with distal accessible HARs (385) and HAR orthologues (372); group II includes genes interacting with non-accessible HARs (324) and HAR orthologues (246); and group III comprises genes near HARs (607) and HAR orthologues (613) without significant chromatin interactions (Fig. 1d,e and Supplementary Table 2). Genes interacting with HARs and their orthologues were enriched in synapse and neuron development pathways (Extended Data Fig.3l) and exhibited similarly higher expression regardless of the chromatin accessibility status of HAR and HAR orthologues than genes without any significant chromatin interactions (Fig. 1e), suggesting the regulatory role of HAR and HAR orthologues. By contrast, genome-wide gene expression analysis shows genes interacting with open chromatin regions that exhibit higher expression than genes interacting with other regions (Fig. 1e). Other conserved non-coding sequences around genes minimally affected the distinct role of HARs and their orthologues in modulating gene expression across groups in both species (Extended Data Fig. 3m). Of note, HAR-interacting genes were enriched for human-upregulated genes, whereas chimpanzee orthologues exhibited no enrichment of human-upregulated or chimpanzee-upregulated genes (Fig. 1f), highlighting the more extensive role of HARs as transcriptional enhancers in human neurons. The prevalence of HAR variants in the human population8 (Extended Data Fig. 3n) prompted us to investigate whether sequence differences between species affect transcription factor-binding affinity. Comparing transcription factor motifs enriched in the 921 HARs and their chimpanzee orthologues from groups I and II revealed enrichment of motifs for the neuron developmental transcription factors, including LHX, EBF and ISL1 families in both species, consistent with their abundant binding sites of these transcription factors in HARs4 (Fig. 1g). By contrast, motifs for SCRT1, PKNOX1 and LEF1, regulators for neuron differentiation, were more enriched in human HARs (Fig. 1g), aligning with earlier predictions of their higher prevalence in HARs4. Conversely, the binding motif for PAX6, a transcription factor involved in neural progenitor cell differentiation, was more enriched in chimpanzee orthologues (Fig. 1g). Thus, species-specific transcription factor
motif enrichment may drive differential gene regulatory programs in neurons.
Characterizing HARs by CRISPRi
We then functionally characterized HARs in neurons using CRISPRi screening coupled with targeted single-cell RNA-seq (HyPR-seq)26. We prioritized 12 HARs with enhancer activities in a previous MPRA study using human neural progenitor cells4 (Fig. 2a and Supplementary Table 3). These HARs are linked to 54 candidate target genes (±1,500 kb centred each HAR), 10 of which are neuronal development or disease-associated genes (Supplementary Table 3). Of these, HAR96, HAR202, 2xHAR.142 and HAR122 are distributed across the introns of NPAS3 (Fig. 3a), the gene with the most accelerated regulatory domain in the human genome27. Furthermore, HAR103, 2xHAR.319 and 2xHAR.155 are located in the most accelerated gene desert region spanning approximately 1 Mb of chromosome 2 (ref. 27) (Fig. 4a), a proposed evolutionarily hotspot flanked by TDRD15 and KLHL29. Beside these 12 HARs, we selected 8 others at distal regions physically interacting with 15 neuronal development or disease-associated genes in human neurons (Fig. 2a and Supplementary Table3). Of these, 2xHAR.11 exhibited human-biased enhancer activity, whereas the 2xHAR.9 orthologue exhibited chimpanzee-biased enhancer activity by MPRA in human neural progenitor cells4. To characterize the roles of HARs on gene expression, we selected 23 putative HAR-targeting genes based on: (1) associated with neuronal development or disease; (2) expressed in human and chimpanzee neurons with transcripts per million > 1; and (3) DAZL, a gene not expressed in neurons with no known brain function but interacts with HAR140 and its orthologue to investigate whether HAR140 acts as a silencer. In summary, 20 HARs and their chimpanzee orthologues were characterized for their effect on the expression of the 23 candidate genes (Fig. 2a and Supplementary Table 3). To achieve comparable CRISPRi efficiencies in both species, we knocked in a CAG-dCas9-KRAB cassette at the CLYBL safe harbour locus in human and chimpanzee i3N iPS cell lines (Extended Data Fig.4a) with comparable CRISPRi knockdown efficiencies (Extended Data Fig.4b). We then designed 40 guide RNAs (gRNAs) targeting 20 HARs (Extended Data Fig.4c as an example) and 6 non-targeting control gRNAs. Neurons differentiated from CRISPRi i3N iPS cell lines were infected with the gRNA lentiviral library at a low multiplicity of infection (MOI = 0.5). To detect gene expression changes, we designed DNA probes against the exons of the aforementioned 23 genes and unique identification barcodes for each gRNA (Extended Data Fig.4d and Supplementary Table4). These probes were hybridized in cells, amplified and sequenced for measuring gene expression and determining gRNA at single-cell resolution. Transcription levels of putative target genes between experimental and control gRNA-treated cells were compared to assessthe regulatory functions of HARs and their orthologues (Extended Data Fig.4e,f). Of the assayed HARs, 14 of 20 exhibited an effect on at least one gene in one species (false discovery rate (FDR) < 0.05). Specifically, 15 target genes were significantly downregulated following perturbation of 12 HARs in human neurons, whereas 4 target genes were significantly downregulated after perturbing 4 HAR orthologues in chimpanzee neurons, suggesting their species-specific enhancer function (Fig. 2b,c and Supplementary Table4). Indeed, bulk CRISPRi and quantitative PCR (qPCR) analyses corroborated their enhancer roles in human neurons, including 2xHAR.63 for ARL8B (Extended Data Fig. 5a), 2xHAR.11 for ONECUT2 (Extended Data Fig. 5b) and HAR140 for TBC1D5 (Extended Data Fig.5c). By contrast, perturbing HAR25 and HAR96 in human neurons and HAR202 and 2xHAR.142 orthologues in chimpanzee neurons upregulated TENM3 and AKAP6, demonstrating their species-specific silencer functions (Fig. 2b,c). Our results confirm the hypothesis that HARs influence human evolution by altering gene expression. The following sections will discuss several examples of HARs exhibiting species-specific cis-regulatory functions in neurons.


4 | Nature | www.nature.com
Article
HAR202 attenuates NPAS3 expression
The identification of the largest HAR cluster, consisting of 22 HARs at the NPAS3 locus, suggests accelerated evolution of the regulatory sequences therein27,28 (Fig. 3a). NPAS3 is the most accelerated gene27,28 expressed in the vertebrate brain29 and is implicated in schizophrenia30. Although NPAS3 expressions were similar in chimpanzee and human iPS cell-induced neurons (Extended Data Fig.6a), its regulatory control could be complex and species specific. To identify regulatory HARs at the NPAS3 locus, we prioritized five HARs for CRISPRi screens based on: (1) HAR144, 2xHAR.122 and their chimpanzee orthologues forming chromatin loops with the NPAS3 promoter in neurons, whereas HAR202 and 2xHAR.142 orthologues exclusively interacting with the NPAS3 promoter in chimpanzee neurons (Fig. 3a); (2) HAR202 and 2xHAR.142 exhibiting differential reporter activities compared with their chimpanzee orthologues27,28; and (3) HAR96 exhibiting the highest enhancer activity among 14 HARs tested in that region in transgenic zebrafish reporter assays27. Single-cell CRISPRi revealed that HAR144, HAR96 and 2xHAR.122, along with their orthologues, did not exhibit regulatory effects on NPAS3 in either human or chimpanzee neurons (Extended Data Fig. 6b). However, HAR144 acted as an enhancer for AKAP6, whereas both HAR96 and 2xHAR.122 functioned as enhancers for ARHGAP5 in human neurons (Fig. 2b). By contrast, the HAR202 orthologue selectively enhanced NPAS3 expression in chimpanzee neurons (Fig. 3b), confirming its enhancer activity from reporter assays in the nervous
system of transgenic zebrafish27. Although our results did not support the enhancer function of 2xHAR.142 for NPAS3 in human neurons, it had an enhancer role for BAZ1A (Fig. 2b), supporting its enhancer activity in the zebrafish nervous system27. We further validated the chimpanzee-specific enhancer function of HAR202 and 2xHAR.142 orthologues for NPAS3 by bulk CRISPRi and qPCR analyses (Fig. 3c and Extended Data Fig. 6c). These findings suggest that HAR202 and 2xHAR.142 act as NPAS3 enhancers in chimpanzee neurons. To dissect the mechanism of species-specific enhancer activity of HAR202, we mapped the differential transcription factor motifs between two species (Supplementary Table 5). Binding motifs of signal transducer and activator of transcription (STAT) family transcription factors, including STAT1, STAT3, STAT5A and STAT5B, were better matched with the HAR202 orthologue (Extended Data Fig.6d). As occupancy of STAT family transcription factors on enhancers can influence their proximal histone modifications and drive chromatin accessibility31, and considering that both human and chimpanzee neurons express these transcription factors (Extended Data Fig. 6e), we hypothesized that the loss of STAT-binding sites during human evolution could explain the reduced enhancer activity of HAR202. STAT3 is the most highly expressed STAT gene in neurons (Extended Data Fig. 6e) and its binding motif aligns better with the two single-nucleotide variants in the chimpanzee HAR202 orthologue (Fig. 3d), in concordance with the greater enrichment of STAT3 in the chimpanzee orthologue than in human HAR202 (Fig. 3e). Disruption of STAT3 binding using the inhibitor S3I-201 (ref. 32) (Fig. 3f), without
