Fig. 2 | Single-cell CRISPRi screens of HARs and chimpanzee orthologues for enhancer function. a, Experimental design and workflow for the CRISPRi screens followed by targeted single-cell RNA-seq (HyPR-seq) in neurons. LentiMPRA, lentivirus-based MPRA. b, Genes exhibited changes in expression after perturbing HARs or their orthologues are shown. Yellow indicates affected human genes, and blue indicates affected chimpanzee genes. Each HAR is labelled with a unique colour. Chr., chromosome. c, Volcano plot showing
the fold changes of gene expression following perturbing HARs and their orthologues (colour labels correspond to the those in panel b), alongside their corresponding −log2(FDR). P values were calculated based on the two-sided, two-sample Student’s t-test and adjusted by Benjamini–Hochberg multiple testing correction. An FDR < 0.05 served as the cut-off for gene expression changes.


Nature | www.nature.com | 5
perturbing STAT3 expression (Fig. 3g), significantly reduced NPAS3 expression in chimpanzee neurons (Fig. 3h). This confirms that STAT3 binding to HAR202 directly affects NPAS3 expression. Furthermore, BCL6 and MEIS2, critical for neurogenesis, were more enriched at HAR202, aligning with their predicted stronger binding affinity to human HAR202 than the chimpanzee orthologue (Extended Data Fig. 6d,f). Finally, the motif for PAX5, another neurogenesis-related transcription factor, better matched the HAR202 orthologue and showed less enrichment in HAR202 (Extended Data Fig.6d,f). Collectively, these results suggest a potential interplay between transcription factors in regulating NPAS3 expression across species, with variants in HAR202 conferring weaker STAT3 and PAX5 binding while promoting BCL6 and MEIS2 recruitment. To understand the role of HAR202 variants on altered enhancer function for NPAS3, we derived heterozygous human iPS cell clones (T/G) of the first variant (hg38 chromosome 14: 33,576,368) by converting one human-specific ‘G’ to the ancestral ‘T’ (Extended Data Fig. 7a–c). We then assessed the effect of this base-pair change on NPAS3 allelic expression leveraging a phased single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP; C/T) in NPAS3 (ref. 33) (Extended Data Fig. 7d,e). Comparing edited and wild-type alleles in the same clone (Extended Data Fig.7e), we showed that G-to-T conversion in HAR202 significantly increases NPAS3 transcription (Fig. 3i). Together, our results demonstrate that a human-specific variant in HAR202 downregulates NPAS3 in cis via affecting transcription factor binding.
HARs as neurodevelopmental enhancers
Gene desert regions are non-coding genomic loci devoid of genes34. The most accelerated gene desert region is densely populated with 17 HARs spanning approximately 2.19 Mb (hg38 chromosome 2: 21,081,993–23,274,710)27 (Fig. 4a). Its adjacent protein-coding genes are enriched for roles in neurogenesis and psychiatric pathogenesis35–37, including (1) PUM2 and SDC1 for neural progenitor cell maintenance and proliferation, (2) RHOB, LAPTM4A and GDF7 for neuronal morphogenesis, and (3) LDAH, APOB, HS1BP3 and WDR35 linked to psychiatric pathogenesis. Recent MPRAs confirm their enhancer activity4,10–12, but their endogenous functions and target genes remain elusive. We prioritized four HARs (2xHAR.319, 2xHAR.155, HAR103 and HAR63) and tested their contribution to LAPTM4A, PUM2 and RHOB expression in neurons based on: (1) 2xHAR.319, 2xHAR.155 and HAR63 showed enhancer activity in neural progenitor cells by MPRAs4, (2) HAR103 showed enhancer activity in neuroblastoma cells by MPRAs10, and (3) 2xHAR.319 and HAR63 overlapped with accessible peaks in both human and chimpanzee neurons25 (Fig. 4a and Extended Data Fig. 8a). Upon CRISPRi perturbation, 2xHAR.319 demonstrated human-specific enhancer activity for PUM2 (Fig. 4b and Supplementary Table4), whereas its chimpanzee orthologue exhibited enhancer activity for LAPTM4A (Extended Data Fig. 8b). These findings are correlated with the greater expression of PUM2 in human neurons
