Fig. 3 | Loss of HAR202 enhancer function in human neurons. a, Location of HARs in the human NPAS3 locus, with those selected for functional characterization in neurons highlighted, is displayed. The WashU Comparative Epigenome Browser snapshot shows chromatin accessibility, interactions and transcriptome at this locus. b, Quantitative effects of HAR202 and its orthologue on NPAS3 expression in neurons. P values were calculated based on the two-sided, two-sample Student’s t-test and adjusted by Benjamini–Hochberg multiple testing correction. The median, upper and lower quantiles are shown by a circle and bar. Each dot represents one single cell. n is indicated in Supplementary Table 4d. NC, cells with negative control gRNAs; UMI, unique molecular identifier. c, NPAS3 expression following CRISPRi perturbing HAR202 and its orthologue in neurons. d, STAT3 motif better matches with two chimpanzee-specific single-nucleotide variants in the HAR202 orthologue. e, Chromatin immunoprecipitation (ChIP)–qPCR assay for STAT3 binding
at HAR202 compared with its orthologue. c, chimpanzee; h, human; IP, immunoprecipitation. f, Schematic representation of STAT3 binding and inhibition by S3I-201. STAT3 enrichment at the HAR202 orthologue in DMSOtreated and S3I-201-treated chimpanzee neurons. P denotes phosphorylation. g,h, STAT3 (g) and NPAS3 (h) expression in DMSO-treated and S3I-201-treated chimpanzee neurons. i, Allelic analysis using haplotype-resolved SNPs in the NPAS3 gene body shows increased NPAS3 expression from the edited allele (T) compared with the wild-type (WT) allele (G) in neurons (data from two clones are shown). The boxplot indicates the median and interquartile range; whiskers mark the 5th and 95th percentiles. PE, prime editing. P values were calculated based on the two-sided Student’s t-test (c,e–i). Three independent biological replicates per condition were used for each experiment (c,e–i). All values represent the mean ± s.d. (c,e–h).


6 | Nature | www.nature.com
Article
(P = 1.24 × 10−3) and the greater expression of LAPTM4A in chimpanzee neurons (P = 0.048; Fig. 4c). In addition, the HAR63 orthologue acted as an enhancer for RHOB exclusively in chimpanzee neurons (Extended Data Fig. 8b). Consistently, the expression of RHOB was significantly decreased upon deleting the HAR63 orthologue in chimpanzee neurons (Extended Data Fig.8c,d). Thus, 2xHAR.319 and HAR63 and their orthologues exhibit species-biased enhancer activities. The function of 2xHAR.319 was also supported by matched motifs for YY1, CEBP, FOS::JUN and SP1 (Extended Data Fig. 8e and Supplementary Table 5). We deleted 2xHAR.319 and its chimpanzee orthologue in human and chimpanzee iPS cells, respectively (Extended Data Fig. 8c). 2xHAR.319-knockout (KO) human iPS cell clones and their differentiated cells exhibited decreased PUM2 expression (Fig. 4d), whereas LAPTM4A and RHOB were unaffected (Extended Data Fig.8d). Furthermore, these iPS cell clones exhibited downregulation of pluripotency genes (SOX2, NANOG and POU5F1), impaired self-renewal, and overexpression of ectodermal (FGF5) and mesodermal (TBXT) markers (Fig. 4e,f). Human 2xHAR.319-KO clones also failed to differentiate
into neurons (Fig. 4f). These phenotypes of 2xHAR.319-KO clones mirror the observed self-renewal deficiency in both human and mouse Pum2-mutated embryonic stem cells38,39, and the role of PUM2 in mouse neurogenesis37. Restoring PUM2 expression through CRISPR-mediated activation (CRISPRa) in human 2xHAR.319-KO cells reestablished iPS cell self-renewal, pluripotency and proper neuronal differentiation (Fig. 4f and Extended Data Fig.8f). In summary, 2xHAR.319 is essential for maintaining human iPS cell pluripotency and neuronal differentiation through its role as a PUM2 enhancer.
HAR26;2xHAR.178 regulates SOCS2
HAR26;2xHAR.178 harbours four variants and is in an open chromatin region that interacts with SOCS2, PLXNC1, CEP83, NDUFA12 and NR2C1 (Fig. 5a and Extended Data Fig. 9a). Except for CEP83, the other four genes are linked to neuronal function or neurological disorders40–43. Of note, Socs2 and Plxnc1 regulate cortical neurite outgrowth in mice40,44,45. SOCS2 expression was elevated in human neurons compared
