with chimpanzee neurons (P = 7.49 × 10−6), whereas no differences in expression of PLXNC1, NDUFA12 and NR2C1 were observed between the two species (Extended Data Fig. 9b). In developing brain tissues, SOCS2 and NDUFA12 have higher brain-wide expression in human compared with chimpanzee, whereas NR2C1 exhibits higher prefrontal cortex-specific expression in human46. In addition, PLXNC1 expression varies across brain tissues for both species46 (Extended Data Fig. 9c). Comparing SOCS2 expression in dorsal telencephalon trajectories between human and non-human primate organoids also showed more cortical neural progenitor cells and neurons with higher SOCS2 expression in humans, especially in cells of late-stage oganoids47 (Extended Data Fig. 9d). Single-cell and bulk CRISPRi experiments in human neurons demonstrated downregulation of all four genes upon HAR26;2xHAR.178 perturbation (Fig. 5b,c, Extended Data Fig.10a and
Supplementary Table 4), supporting the human-specific enhancer function of HAR26;2xHAR.178. To interrogate the regulatory function of four variants in HAR26; 2xHAR.178, we generated humanized chimpanzee iPS cell clones by individually knocking in each human variant in chimpanzee iPS cells (PE1–PE4; Fig. 5a), converting homozygous chimpanzee alleles to heterozygous (Extended Data Fig. 10b). We then assessed the effect of variants on gene expression leveraging phased SNPs. Variant-specific cis-regulatory effects were observed: humanizing PE1 significantly increased the allelic expression ratio of SOCS2 (P = 0.003) and NDUFA12 (P = 0.003), whereas PE2 significantly increased the allelic expression ratio of PLXNC1 (P = 0.04; Fig. 5d and Extended Data Fig.10c) between edited and wild-type chimpanzee allele. In addition, PE2 and PE4 confer opposite effects on NDUFA12 (Extended Data Fig. 10c) and SOCS2
