Fig. 5 | HAR26;2xHAR.178 upregulates SOCS2 and enhanced neuritogenesis. a, Chromatin interactions of HAR26;2xHAR.178 with four neuronal functions and psychiatric disorder-related genes in humans (also shown in Extended Data Fig. 9a). Four variants in HAR26;2xHAR.178 are shown. b, Quantitative effects of HAR26;2xHAR.178 on SOCS2 and PLXNC1 expression in neurons. The median, upper and lower quantiles are shown by a circle and bar. Each dot represents one single cell. n is indicated in Supplementary Table 4d. c, Validation of HAR26;2xHAR.178 and its orthologue function on SOCS2 and PLXNC1 expression in neurons by CRISPRi. d, Allelic analysis using haplotype-resolved SNPs in gene bodies shows the effects of each variant on SOC2 and PLXNC1 expression between the edited and the WT alleles in humanized chimpanzee neurons. The boxplot indicates the median and interquartile range; whiskers mark the 5th and 95th percentiles. Data were generated with three edited clones for each
genotyping. e, NR2F1 and TFAP2A motif better match with HAR26;2xHAR.178 than its chimpanzee orthologue. f, Anti-NR2F1 and TFAP2A ChIP–qPCR in WT and humanized chimpanzee neurons. g, Representative images of GFP-labelling of neurons in PE1-edited chimpanzee neurons compared with WT chimpanzee and human neurons. Scale bars, 10 μM. h, Quantifying neurite numbers in PE1edited chimpanzee, WT chimpanzee and human neurons. Data are presented as the average number of processes per neuron intersecting at a given radius centred on the soma. Error bars indicate mean ± s.e.m. n = 15 cells per sample. i, Working model for HAR26;2xHAR.178-mediated regulation of neuritogenesis. P values were calculated using the two-sided, two-sampleStudent’s t-test (c,d,f,h) and adjusted by Benjamini–Hochberg multiple testing correction (d). Three independent biological replicates per condition were used for each experiment (c,f). All values represent the mean ± s.d. (c,f).


8 | Nature | www.nature.com
Article
(Fig. 5d) expression, respectively, supporting the compensatory evolution theory of HARs4. To substantiate this, we generated PE1–PE4 and PE1–PE2 double prime-edited clones (Extended Data Fig. 10d) and assessed their effect on SOCS2 and NDUFA12 expression, respectively. As expected, PE1–PE4 double-edited clones (n = 3) showed an attenuated increase in SOCS2 expression compared with PE1 single-edited clones (n = 3; Extended Data Fig. 10e), whereas NDUFA12 expression was similarly affected in both PE1–PE2 double-edited (n = 3) and PE1 single-edited clones (n = 3), possibly because PE1 exerts a more profound effect on NDUFA12 expression, masking the negative regulation caused by PE2 (Extended Data Fig. 10e). We explored transcription factor-binding motifs in HAR26;2xHAR.178 (Supplementary Table5) and found PE1 and PE2 better matched NR2F1 and TFAP2A motifs, respectively (Fig. 5e). Both transcription factors are expressed in human and chimpanzee neurons (Extended Data Fig.10f), and their co-occupancy links to permissive enhancer chromatin states48. We hypothesized that the HAR26;2xHAR.178 locus gained a higher affinity for NR2F1 and TFAP2A binding during human evolution. This can be confirmed by the increased binding of NR2F1 and TFAP2A in humanized chimpanzee neurons, comparable with their enrichment in human neurons (Fig. 5f). Human iPS cell-induced neurons exhibited increased neurite outgrowth compared with chimpanzee neurons by Neurite Tracer and Sholl analysis49 (Fig. 5g,h). This difference was attributed to the elevated expression of SOCS2, as SOCS2 knockdown reduced neuritogenesis in human neurons (Extended Data Fig. 10g–i). Humanized (PE1) chimpanzee neurons exhibit significantly increased neurite branching compared with wild-type chimpanzee neurons (Fig. 5h and Extended Data Fig. 10j). As expected, neurons of PE1–PE4 double-edited clones demonstrated attenuated neurite growth compared with neurons of PE1 single-edited clones (Extended Data Fig. 10k,l), consistent with the SOCS2 levels in these clones. These results confirm the role of HAR26;2xHAR.178 as an evolutionary enhancer regulating neural genes, for example, SOCS2, an important regulator of neuritogenesis (Fig. 5i).
Discussion
In this study, we investigated the mechanisms underlying HAR-mediated cis-regulation in neurons. By comparing regulatory functions between HARs and their chimpanzee orthologues, we identified 12 HAR enhancers regulating 15 target genes in human neurons and 4 chimpanzee HAR orthologues regulating 4 target genes in chimpanzee neurons. We also functionally characterized the phenotypic consequences of HARs and their differential regulation of target genes in excitatory neurons. In particular, we have demonstrated that the cis-regulatory function of HAR26;2xHAR.178 results in enhanced SOCS2 expression and neuritogenesis, an essential process during human brain development. MPRA-based high-throughput methods enable the regulatory annotation of HARs outside their native chromatin context, which is insufficient for identifying HAR target genes4,10–12. Our high-resolution chromatin interaction analysis represents a major advance in the comparative characterization of HARs and the endogenous targets of their orthologues in human and chimpanzee neurons, respectively. Using single-cell CRISPRi screens, we quantified the differential regulatory capabilities of previously uncharacterized HARs between species. Finally, by introducing species-specific variants in iPS cells, we have provided novel models to study HAR endogenous regulatory activity at base-pair resolution. The observation that multiple variants within the same HAR can confer opposing effects on enhancer activity has been proposed as a form of compensatory evolution in which HARs maintain ancestral enhancer activity via transcription factor binding sitemodifications4. In line with this theory, our prime-editing results revealed opposite cis-regulatory effects of individual variants within HAR26;2xHAR.178
on SOCS2 and NDUFA12 expression. Moreover, we have demonstrated that HAR202 and 2xHAR.142, two closely located HARs (2.88 kb part) in an NPAS3 intron, upregulated the expression of BAZ1A and PSMA6 in human neurons; however, their chimpanzee orthologues instead upregulated NPAS3 expression while downregulating the nearby AKAP6 expression. Although these HARs do not precisely fulfil the criteria for compensatory evolution, from an evolutionary point of view, they imply an alternative mechanism in which the human-specific variants may act to maintain ancestral enhancer function by inducing the regulation of different target genes. Together, our findings support the compensatory evolution theory of HARs. Further characterization of the opposing, synergistic and redundant effects of HAR variants on gene expression is still warranted. Finally, our prime-editing experiments demonstrate that the regulatory effects of HARs on endogenous target genes are associated with enhanced neuritogenesis. Expanding research to other brain cell types, neurodevelopmental stages and invivo models, along with exploring other rapidly evolved loci, such as human ancestor quickly evolved regions50, holds the potential to deepen our understanding of the roles of HARs in mediating the enigmatic process of human brain evolution.
